cs.SI, cs.DL, cs.SD, cs.IR, cs.CY

The paper discusses a new method for visualizing the relatedness of scientific areas based on measuring the overlap of researchers between areas. This method involves statistical analysis and network mapping, which are commonly used in several sub-categories of computer science. Specifically, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.DL (Digital Libraries) are likely sub-categories as they deal with network analysis and information retrieval. cs.SD (Software Engineering) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval) are also possible sub-categories as they involve statistical analysis and data mining. Finally, cs.CY (Computers and Society) is a potential sub-category as the paper discusses the multidisciplinary nature of complexity science, which may involve societal implications.
